    {"parentUuid":"24a90f5e-de01-4a81-860d-81d5441a4d72","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b51d0d0e-11a7-49cc-a304-5ddf3d02ce8f","agentId":"a8ac571b47a56ba8a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01N5pXtURwzQaPrE5xUug8jB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Consolidated Reference List\n2\t\n3\tAll references from the prime-research project, deduplicated and organized by category.\n4\tEach entry includes author(s), title, year, source, and relevance to the project.\n5\t\n6\tLast updated: 2026-04-04\n7\t\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t## 1. Algorithms for pi(x) and p(n)\n11\t\n12\t**Legendre, A.-M.** \"Essai sur la theorie des nombres.\" 1808.\n13\tRecursive inclusion-exclusion formula for pi(x), O(x^{3/4}). Foundation of all combinatorial pi(x) methods.\n14\t\n15\t**Meissel, E.** Combinatorial decomposition for pi(x). 1870-1885.\n16\tSplit contributions by number of prime factors, achieving O(x/(log x)^3). First sublinear pi(x) method.\n17\t\n18\t**Lehmer, D. H.** Extension of Meissel's method with P3 term. 1959.\n19\tImproved to O(x/(log x)^4). Basis of all modern combinatorial pi(x) implementations.\n20\t\n21\t**Lagarias, J.; Miller, V.; Odlyzko, A.** \"Computing pi(x): The Meissel-Lehmer Method.\" 1985.\n22\tAchieved O(x^{2/3}/log x) via improved combinatorial identities.\n23\t\n24\t**Lagarias, J.; Odlyzko, A.** \"Computing pi(x): An Analytic Method.\" J. reine angew. Math. 387, 1987. [PDF](https://www-users.cse.umn.edu/~odlyzko/doc/arch/analytic.pi.of.x.pdf)\n25\tFirst O(x^{1/2+eps}) algorithm for pi(x) using Perron's formula and zeta zeros. Theoretical best upper bound; never implemented by its authors due to large constants.\n26\t\n27\t**Deleglise, M.; Rivat, J.** \"Computing pi(x): The Meissel, Lehmer, Lagarias, Miller, Odlyzko method.\" Math. Comp. 65, 1996. [PDF](https://cr.yp.to/bib/1996/deleglise.pdf)\n28\tRefined combinatorial method to O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x). Current best practical asymptotic for combinatorial pi(x).\n29\t\n30\t**Gourdon, X.** Implementation of an improved Deleglise-Rivat variant. 2001.\n31\tO(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) with different space tradeoffs. Used in primecount library.\n32\t\n33\t**Lucy_Hedgehog.** Iterative DP algorithm for pi(x). 2012 (Project Euler community). [Analysis](https://gbroxey.github.io/blog/2023/04/09/lucy-fenwick.html)\n34\tO(x^{2/3}) time, O(x^{1/2}) space, ~15 lines of code. Exploits that floor(x/k) takes O(sqrt(x)) distinct values. Widely used in competitive programming.\n35\t\n36\t**Platt, D.; Trudgian, T.** \"Computing pi(x) Analytically.\" 2012. [arXiv:1203.5712](https://arxiv.org/abs/1203.5712)\n37\tRigorous interval-arithmetic implementation of analytic pi(x). Computed pi(10^25) unconditionally.\n38\t\n39\t**Walisch, K.** primecount library. [GitHub](https://github.com/kimwalisch/primecount)\n40\tState-of-art implementation of Deleglise-Rivat and Gourdon algorithms. Parallelized, computes pi(10^25) in 330 CPU core hours. Versions 8.0-8.4 (2025-2026) added 128-bit API, SIMD Gourdon D formula, AVX512/ARM SVE support.\n41\t\n42\t**Aggarwal, A.** \"A Note on Algorithms for Computing p_n.\" arXiv:2510.16285, October 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.16285)\n43\tProves p(n) computable in O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^4) via binary search on pi(x). Conditional: O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^{7/2} * log log n) under RH + Cramer. Proves sieve-based methods cannot beat binary-search-on-pi(x) asymptotically.\n44\t\n45\t---\n46\t\n47\t## 2. Complexity Theory and Lower Bounds\n48\t\n49\t**Agrawal, N.; Kayal, N.; Saxena, N.** \"PRIMES is in P.\" Annals of Mathematics 160, 2002. [PDF](https://www.cse.iitk.ac.in/users/manindra/algebra/primality_v6.pdf)\n50\tAKS deterministic primality test in O~(log^6 n). Proved PRIMES is in P, but does not help with counting primes.\n51\t\n52\t**Allender, E.; Saks, M.; Shparlinski, I.** \"A Lower Bound for Primality.\" J. Comput. Sys. Sci. 62, 2001. [ScienceDirect](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022000000917252)\n53\tPRIMES is NOT in AC^0[p] for any prime p. Best known unconditional circuit lower bound for primality.\n54\t\n55\t**Hesse, W.; Allender, E.; Barrington, D.** \"Division is in Uniform TC^0.\" J. Comput. Sys. Sci. 65, 2002. [ScienceDirect](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022000002000259)\n56\tDivision and iterated multiplication in uniform TC^0. Context for circuit complexity of arithmetic primitives.\n57\t\n58\t**Agrawal, M.; Allender, E. et al.** \"On TC0, AC0, and Arithmetic Circuits.\" [PDF](https://people.cs.rutgers.edu/~allender/papers/arithmetic.pdf)\n59\tFramework for understanding arithmetic circuit complexity. Relevant to whether pi(x) can be parallelized (NC question).\n60\t\n61\t**Mauduit, C.; Rivat, J.** \"Sur un probleme de Gelfond: la somme des chiffres des nombres premiers.\" Annals of Mathematics 171, 2010.\n62\tProved primes are NOT k-automatic for any k. Rules out finite-automaton-based approaches.\n63\t\n64\t**Raz, R.** \"Natural Proofs for Super-Linear Lower Bounds on Linear Functions.\" ECCC TR26-008, January 2026. [ECCC](https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/report/2026/008/)\n65\tFirst formalization of natural proof barriers for linear circuit complexity. Shows what approaches cannot work for proving super-linear lower bounds on linear functions over finite fields.\n66\t\n67\t**Chen, L.; Tal, A.; Wang, Y.** \"Super-Quadratic Lower Bounds for Depth-2 Linear Threshold Circuits.\" ECCC TR26-039, March 2026. [ECCC](https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/report/2026/039/)\n68\tFunction in E^NP requiring n^{2.5-eps}-size THR-of-THR circuits. Strongest known lower bound for depth-2 linear threshold model.\n69\t\n70\t---\n71\t\n72\t## 3. Exact Formulas for Primes\n73\t\n74\t**Mills, W. H.** \"A Prime-Representing Function.\" Bull. Amer. Math. Soc. 53, 604, 1947.\n75\tfloor(A^{3^n}) is prime for all n. Circular: constant A encodes the primes.\n76\t\n77\t**Wright, E. M.** \"A Prime-Representing Function.\" Amer. Math. Monthly 58, 616-618, 1951.\n78\tIterated-exponential prime formula. Same circularity as Mills.\n79\t\n80\t**Robinson, J.** Arithmetic terms for number-theoretic functions. 1952.\n81\tShowed binomial coefficients have arithmetic term representations: C(a,b) = floor((2^a+1)^a / 2^(ab)) mod 2^a. Foundation for Prunescu-Shunia.\n82\t\n83\t**Willans, C. P.** \"A Formula for the Nth Prime Number.\" Math. Gaz. 48, 413-415, 1964.\n84\tWilson-based formula. O(4^n * n!) -- computationally useless beyond p(6), but proves a formula exists.\n85\t\n86\t**Gandhi, J. M.** \"Formulae for the Nth Prime.\" Proc. Washington State Univ. Conf. Number Theory, 96-106, 1971.\n87\tPrimorial recurrence using Mobius function. Exact but exponential in primorial; infeasible beyond p(8).\n88\t\n89\t**Jones, J. P.** \"Formula for the Nth Prime Number.\" Canad. Math. Bull. 18, 433-434, 1975.\n90\tCompact Wilson variant using monus operator and Bertrand's postulate bound n^2.\n91\t\n92\t**Jones, J. P.; Sato, D.; Wada, H.; Wiens, D.** \"Diophantine Representation of the Set of Prime Numbers.\" Amer. Math. Monthly 83, 449-464, 1976.\n93\tPolynomial of degree 25 in 26 variables whose positive values are exactly the primes. Solutions involve numbers ~10^{10^52}; computationally impossible.\n94\t\n95\t**Golomb, S. W.** Zeta-based recurrence for primes. 1976.\n96\tRequires knowing prior primes; non-constructive limit.\n97\t\n98\t**Conway, J. H.** \"FRACTRAN: A Simple Universal Programming Language for Arithmetic.\" Open Problems in Communication and Computation, Springer, 1987. [OEIS](https://oeis.org/wiki/Conway's_PRIMEGAME)\n99\t14-fraction program producing primes. Turing-complete but O(p^2) per prime.\n100\t\n101\t**Mazzanti, S.** \"Plain Bases for Classes of Primitive Recursive Functions.\" Math. Logic Quarterly 48, 2002.\n102\tProved all Kalmar elementary functions have arithmetic term representations (non-constructive). Theoretical basis for Prunescu-Shunia.\n103\t\n104\t**Rowland, E. S.** \"A Natural Prime-Generating Recurrence.\" J. Integer Seq. 11, 2008.\n105\tGCD recurrence a(n) = a(n-1) + gcd(n, a(n-1)). Produces only primes but misses many; 18 distinct primes in 100,000 terms.\n106\t\n107\t**Plouffe, S.** \"A formula for primes.\" arXiv:1901.01849, 2018 (revised 2022). [PDF](http://plouffe.fr/articles/Formula%20for%20primes.pdf)\n108\tExponential formulas {a_0 * r^n} with r=5/4 producing 50 probable primes. Conjectured, not proven. Constant-dependent.\n109\t\n110\t**Fridman, D.; Garbulsky, J.; Glecer, B.; Grime, J.** \"A Prime-Representing Constant.\" Amer. Math. Monthly 126, 70-73, 2019.\n111\tElegant fractional expansion revealing successive primes. Circular: computing the constant requires knowing primes.\n112\t\n113\t**Elsholtz, C.** \"Unconditional Prime-Representing Functions.\" Bull. London Math. Soc. 52, 2020.\n114\tMills-type formula proved without RH. Same constant-dependency problem.\n115\t\n116\t**Prunescu, M.; Sauras-Altuzarra, L.** \"An Arithmetic Term for the Factorial Function.\" J. Integer Seq., 2024. [ScienceDirect](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2666657X24000028)\n117\tFirst explicit arithmetic term for n!. Building block for the prime formula.\n118\t\n119\t**Prunescu, M.; Shunia, J. M.** \"On arithmetic terms expressing the prime-counting function and the n-th prime.\" arXiv:2412.14594, December 2024; J. Integer Seq. 28, Article 25.5.3, 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.14594) [JIS](https://cs.uwaterloo.ca/journals/JIS/VOL28/Prunescu/prunescu3.pdf)\n120\tFirst explicit fixed-length arithmetic terms for pi(n) and p(n) using only +, -, *, div, exp. Tower-of-exponentials intermediate values make evaluation impossible for any non-trivial input.\n121\t\n122\t**Prunescu, M.; Shunia, J. M.** \"Computational considerations on arithmetic terms for number-theoretic functions.\" J. Logic & Computation 35(3), April 2025. [Oxford](https://academic.oup.com/logcom/article-abstract/35/3/exaf012/8071363)\n123\tArithmetic terms for tau(n), sigma(n), phi(n), modular inverse, integer root, discrete logarithm.\n124\t\n125\t**Prunescu, M.; Shunia, J. M.** \"Elementary closed-forms for non-trivial divisors.\" arXiv:2510.26939, October 2025.\n126\tArithmetic terms for smallest/largest prime divisor. O(1) operations but O(2^n) time due to intermediate values.\n127\t\n128\t**Prunescu, M.; Shunia, J. M.** \"On the representation of number-theoretic functions by arithmetic terms.\" arXiv:2407.12928, July 2024. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.12928)\n129\tArithmetic terms for GCD function.\n130\t\n131\t**Prunescu, M.** \"Arithmetic closed forms count the Mersenne primes, the Fermat primes and the twin-prime pairs.\" arXiv:2512.01680, December 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.01680)\n132\tExtended arithmetic term framework to special prime classes using Lucas-Lehmer, Pepin, Clement tests.\n133\t\n134\t**Semenov, S.** \"Smooth Analytical Approximation of Prime Characteristic Function.\" arXiv:2504.14414, April 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.14414)\n135\tSmooth function P(n) via triple integral with periodic kernel: P(n) -> 1 for primes, P(n) < 1 for composites. Not a finite closed-form; evaluation cost at least as expensive as trial division.\n136\t\n137\t---\n138\t\n139\t## 4. Sieve Methods and Prime Distribution\n140\t\n141\t**Maynard, J.; Tao, T.** Bounded gaps between primes. 2013-2014.\n142\tInfinitely many prime pairs with gap <= 246. Sieve-based (weighted Selberg sieve).\n143\t\n144\t**Craig, W.; Ono, K.; van Ittersum, J.-W.** \"Integer partitions detect the primes.\" PNAS, September 2024. arXiv:2405.06451. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.06451) [PNAS](https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.2409417121)\n145\tPrimes are solutions to Diophantine equations in MacMahon partition functions. Infinitely many new prime characterizations. Structural, not computational.\n146\t\n147\t**Lichtman, J. D.** \"A modified linear sieve.\" Algebra & Number Theory 19(1), 2025. arXiv:2109.02851. [ANT](https://msp.org/ant/2025/19-1/ant-v19-n1-p01-p.pdf)\n148\tEquidistributes primes in arithmetic progressions to moduli up to x^{10/17}, surpassing the x^{7/12} barrier. Largest improvement to twin prime upper bound since 1986.\n149\t\n150\t**Pascadi, A.** \"Primes and smooth numbers to x^{5/8}.\" arXiv:2505.00653, May 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.00653)\n151\tEquidistribution to moduli x^{5/8} without Selberg eigenvalue conjecture. Uses triply-well-factorable weights.\n152\t\n153\t**Bouras, M.** \"A new primes-generating sequence.\" arXiv:2509.09745, 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.09745)\n154\tGCD-based recurrence producing only 1s and primes. Improvement over Rowland but still incomplete.\n155\t\n156\t**Tao, T.; Teravainen, J.** \"Quantitative Correlations on Prime Factors of Consecutive Integers.\" arXiv:2512.01739, December 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.01739)\n157\tResolves multiple Erdos conjectures: omega(n+k) <= k infinitely often, irrationality of sum omega(n)/2^n, asymptotic for consecutive integers with equal prime divisor counts.\n158\t\n159\t**Volfson, V.** \"Generalization of Hardy-Littlewood Conjecture to Almost-Prime Tuples.\" arXiv:2603.13416, March 2026. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.13416)\n160\tExtends Hardy-Littlewood k-tuple conjecture to almost-primes with Selberg constant correction factors.\n161\t\n162\t**Hakobyan, T.** \"Almost Prime Numbers.\" arXiv:2603.00679, February 2026. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.00679)\n163\tNew generalization of primality; shows composite almost-primes must be Carmichael numbers.\n164\t\n165\t**Li, R.** \"Prime-Producing Sieves and Distribution of alpha*p - beta mod 1.\" arXiv:2504.13195, April 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.13195)\n166\tInfinitely many primes p with ||alpha*p - beta|| < p^{-28/87}. Sharpens Jia (2000) using minimal Type-II information.\n167\t\n168\t**Gensel, B.** \"The Prime Number Formula of Gandhi.\" arXiv:1910.08362, 2019.\n169\tExposition and simplification of Gandhi's primorial formula.\n170\t\n171\t**Jakimczuk, R.** \"Generalizations of the Gandhi Formula.\" 2024.\n172\tExtensions of the Gandhi primorial recurrence.\n173\t\n174\t---\n175\t\n176\t## 5. Analytic Number Theory and Zeta Function\n177\t\n178\t**Cloitre, B.** \"An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers.\" arXiv:2508.02690, 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.02690)\n179\tFirst proven effective analytic recurrence: p(n+1) via zeta evaluation and Euler product over prior primes. Exact for all n but requires extreme-precision arithmetic.\n180\t\n181\t**Saito, K.** \"Mills' constant is irrational.\" arXiv:2404.19461, April 2024; Mathematika 71(3), 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.19461)\n182\tResolved a long-standing open problem. Partial transcendence results obtained.\n183\t\n184\t**Visser, M.** \"The nth Prime Exponentially.\" Mathematics (MDPI) 13(11), 1844, 2025. [MDPI](https://www.mdpi.com/2227-7390/13/11/1844)\n185\tExponentially tight explicit bounds on p(n) location. Useful for narrowing binary search.\n186\t\n187\t**Visser, M.** \"Effective exponential bounds on the prime gaps.\" International Mathematical Forum, 2025. [PDF](https://www.m-hikari.com/imf/imf-2025/1-4-2025/p/visserIMF1-4-2025.pdf)\n188\tExplicit bounds on g(n) = p(n+1) - p(n) with exponential factors and proven validity ranges.\n189\t\n190\t**Visser, M.** \"Behaviour of the sequence theta_n = theta(p_n).\" arXiv:2507.14410, July 2025.\n191\tAnalysis of Chebyshev's theta function at primes.\n192\t\n193\t**Explicit formula for zeta zeros via Hermite polynomials.** arXiv:2312.00108; Ramanujan Journal, 2025. [Springer](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11139-025-01297-y)\n194\tClaims primes determine zero distribution and zeros can be computed without using zeta directly. Could simplify analytic pi(x) pipeline.\n195\t\n196\t**Connes, A.** \"The Riemann Hypothesis: Past, Present and a Letter Through Time.\" arXiv:2602.04022, February 2026. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.04022)\n197\t42-page survey. Novel: approximates first 50 zeta zeros from primes < 13 to 10^{-55} accuracy using Weil quadratic form. Does not provide computational speedup for pi(x).\n198\t\n199\t**Bailleul, A.; Hayani, M.; Untrau, T.** \"Wasserstein Approach to Generalized Skewes Numbers.\" arXiv:2603.20093, March 2026. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.20093)\n200\tUnconditionally disproves Fiorilli conjecture. Conditional upper bounds for generalized Skewes numbers using quantitative Kronecker-Weyl theorem in 1-Wasserstein metric.\n201\t\n202\t**Vartziotis, D.** \"Fourier Series from Additive Prime Factor Functions.\" arXiv:2602.13342, February 2026. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.13342)\n203\tSparse prime-indexed Fourier series from sopfr(n). Exact decomposition of summatory function B(n) ~ pi^2 x^2/(12 log x). See also companion: arXiv:2602.21270.\n204\t\n205\t**Li, Z.** \"Deterministic Fractal Set from Prime Number Sequence.\" arXiv:2603.00658, February 2026. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.00658)\n206\tCantor-like fractal from primes mod 16 with universal Hausdorff dimension 1/4, independent of specific prime residue sequence.\n207\t\n208\t---\n209\t\n210\t## 6. 2024-2026 Breakthroughs\n211\t\n212\t**Guth, L.; Maynard, J.** \"New large value estimates for Dirichlet polynomials.\" arXiv:2405.20552, May 2024; Annals of Mathematics, 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.20552) [Annals](https://annals.math.princeton.edu/articles/22049)\n213\tImproved Ingham zero-density bound from 3/5 to 13/25 -- first improvement in 80+ years. PNT in short intervals [x, x+x^{17/30}]. Most significant advance in analytic number theory in 2024.\n214\t\n215\t**Gafni, A.; Tao, T.** \"Exceptional intervals for the prime number theorem in short intervals.\" arXiv:2505.24017, May 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.24017)\n216\tExplicit quantitative relationship between zero density estimates and exceptional PNT failures. Uses Guth-Maynard estimates.\n217\t\n218\t**Le Duc Hieu.** \"Arithmetic progressions of primes in short intervals beyond 17/30.\" arXiv:2509.04883, September 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.04883)\n219\tCombines uniform short-interval PNT at theta > 17/30 with Green-Tao transference principle.\n220\t\n221\t---\n222\t\n223\t## 7. Quantum Computing\n224\t\n225\t**Nayak, A.; Wu, F.** Quantum lower bound: Omega(sqrt(x)) queries for functions with prime structure.\n226\tProves quantum speedup is at most quadratic over classical for counting-type problems.\n227\t\n228\t**Berry-Keating conjecture.** Hypothetical Hamiltonian whose eigenvalues are zeta zeros.\n229\tEven if it exists, would need ~10^51 eigenvalues for p(10^100). No efficient quantum simulation known.\n230\t\n231\t---\n232\t\n233\t## 8. Information Theory and ML\n234\t\n235\t**Prime Coding Theorem.** arXiv:2308.10817, 2023.\n236\tInformation content of prime sequence exceeds any learnable pattern. Explains why ML cannot discover a prime formula.\n237\t\n238\t**Prime classification with sparse encoding.** arXiv:2402.03363, 2024 (WITHDRAWN).\n239\tResNet + Transformer for prime/non-prime classification. ~99% recall, never 100%. Withdrawn by authors.\n240\t\n241\t**AI in Number Theory: LLMs for Algorithm Generation.** arXiv:2504.19451, April 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.19451)\n242\tQwen2.5-Math-7B achieves >= 0.95 accuracy on algorithmic number theory tasks with optimal hints. LightGBM classifier achieves >= 93.9% accuracy identifying Dirichlet character modulus from L-function zeros.\n243\t\n244\t**Google DeepMind.** \"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-Powered Coding Agent for Designing Advanced Algorithms.\" arXiv:2506.13131, 2025. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.13131)\n245\tEvolutionary algorithm discovery: 4x4 matrix multiplication in 48 scalar ops (breaking Strassen), improved solutions on 50+ open problems. Not yet applied to prime computation.\n246\t\n247\t---\n248\t\n249\t## 9. Summatory Functions and Related\n250\t\n251\t**Computation of Totient Summatory Function.** arXiv:2506.07386.\n252\tRelated O(x^{2/3}) method for Euler totient sum. Same barrier as pi(x).\n253\t\n254\t**Griff's blog on summing multiplicative functions.** [Blog](https://gbroxey.github.io/blog/2023/04/30/mult-sum-1.html)\n255\tPractical techniques for summatory functions using Dirichlet hyperbola method.\n256\t\n257\t---\n258\t\n259\t## 10. General References and Surveys\n260\t\n261\t- [Prime-counting function (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime-counting_function)\n262\t- [Formula for primes (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formula_for_primes)\n263\t- [Primality test (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primality_test)\n264\t- [NC complexity (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NC_(complexity))\n265\t- [FRACTRAN (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FRACTRAN)\n266\t- [Mills' constant (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mills'_constant)\n267\t- [Meissel-Lehmer algorithm (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meissel%E2%80%93Lehmer_algorithm)\n268\t- [Analytic Computation of pi(x) (Uni Bonn)](https://www.math.uni-bonn.de/people/jbuethe/topics/AnalyticPiX.html)\n269\t- [Wolfram MathWorld: Prime Formulas](https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeFormulas.html)\n270\t- [Wolfram MathWorld: Prime Diophantine Equations](https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeDiophantineEquations.html)\n271\t- [Willans' Formula (MathWorld)](https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WillansFormula.html)\n272\t- [FAQ: Is there a formula for the nth prime?](https://t5k.org/notes/faq/p_n.html)\n273\t- [Quanta: Sensational proof delivers new insights into prime numbers (2024)](https://www.quantamagazine.org/sensational-proof-delivers-new-insights-into-prime-numbers-20240715/)\n274\t- [Quanta: Mathematicians uncover a new way to count prime numbers (2024)](https://www.quantamagazine.org/mathematicians-uncover-a-new-way-to-count-prime-numbers-20241211/)\n275\t- [Scientific American: Top 10 Math Discoveries of 2025](https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/the-top-10-math-discoveries-of-2025/)\n276\t- [AMS Notices on partition primes (June 2025)](https://www.ams.org/journals/notices/202506/noti3198/noti3198.html)\n277\t- [Modern Breakthroughs in Prime Gaps (2025, Mathematics Magazine)](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/0025570X.2025.2481010)\n278\t- [Shunia's blog on prime formula](https://www.josephshunia.com/2024/08/10/an-easy-formula-for-prime-numbers/)\n279\t- [Shunia's GitHub](https://github.com/jshunia)\n280\t\n281\t---\n282\t\n283\tGenerated: 2026-04-04\n284\tSources: FINDINGS.md, all_known_exact_formulas.md, arithmetic_pi_formula.md, combinatorial_formulas.md, recursive_formulas.md, prunescu_shunia_formula.md, complexity_of_primes.md, latest_2026_breakthroughs.md, latest_research_2026.md, exact_formulas_2026.md, exact_formulas_research.md, april_2026_new_findings.md, session10_internet_search.md\n285\t"}]},"uuid":"e57f8fb9-868f-4a6a-aef2-f1786980be9d","timestamp":"2026-04-04T15:11:20.763Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"24a90f5e-de01-4a81-860d-81d5441a4d72","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"33140f23-a580-4bd9-95f3-32a2246a99e4","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"majestic-juggling-whale"}
