    {"parentUuid":"9ab58436-feac-4e13-854b-d18096955aae","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b51d0d0e-11a7-49cc-a304-5ddf3d02ce8f","agentId":"a9a175726ae9963f1","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CJktMxNX6wUbBgXWczFtmS","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Lucy_Hedgehog DP prime counting function O(x^{2/3}) improvement summatory multiplicative function\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Lucy's Algorithm + Fenwick Trees | griff's math blog!\",\"url\":\"https://gbroxey.github.io/blog/2023/04/09/lucy-fenwick.html\"},{\"title\":\"Yet another prime counting program, range based\",\"url\":\"https://comp.lang.forth.narkive.com/SWeOfcJ4/yet-another-prime-counting-program-range-based\"},{\"title\":\"Editorial - Toyota Programming Contest 2024#9（AtCoder Beginner Contest 370）\",\"url\":\"https://atcoder.jp/contests/abc370/editorial/10906\"},{\"title\":\"Jacob Elafandi: Project Euler, Problem 10\",\"url\":\"https://math.berkeley.edu/~elafandi/euler/p10/\"},{\"title\":\"Prime counting function - OeisWiki\",\"url\":\"https://oeis.org/wiki/Prime_counting_function\"},{\"title\":\"1 / 70 導入 素数の数え上げ 乗法的関数の和 Lucy DPの高速化 乗法的関数の和の高速化 実験 おわり 素数の数え上げと乗法的関数の和\",\"url\":\"https://rsk0315.github.io/slides/prime-counting.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - Gautam-1/fast-nth-prime_Cryptography_Aut25: A high-performance, pure Python implementation to find the N-th prime number using the Meissel-Lehmer algorithm (Iterative / Lucy Hedgehog variant) and Binary Search. Complexity: O(N^(3/4)).\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Gautam-1/fast-nth-prime_Cryptography_Aut25\"},{\"title\":\"Lucy’s Algorithm + Fenwick Trees\",\"url\":\"https://gbroxey-github-io.translate.goog/blog/2023/04/09/lucy-fenwick.html?_x_tr_sl=en&_x_tr_tl=es&_x_tr_hl=es&_x_tr_pto=tc\"},{\"title\":\"Counting primes in $$$\\\\tilde{{\\\\cal O}}(n^{2/3}\\\\,\\\\,)$$$ - Codeforces\",\"url\":\"https://codeforces.com/blog/entry/91632\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - AaronChen0/primecount: Prime counting of sublinear complexity in Common Lisp.\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/AaronChen0/primecount\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found comprehensive information about Lucy_Hedgehog's algorithm for prime counting and its improvements:\n\n## Lucy_Hedgehog DP Algorithm Overview\n\nLucy_Hedgehog's algorithm, originally posted on Project Euler's Problem 10 forum, was designed to compute the sum of primes under a given number.\n\n## Prime Counting Function with O(x^{2/3}) Complexity\n\nLucy_Hedgehog's algorithm can be optimized using Fenwick trees to achieve a final runtime of at most O(x^{2/3} (log x)^{1/3}) to compute π(x).\n\n## Lucy DP and Multiplicative Functions\n\nLucy DP originates from a post by Lucy_Hedgehog in the thread of Project Euler: Problem 10. The algorithm can be applied to summatory multiplicative functions. The Min_25 sieve does an inverse of Lucy DP and computes the sum of f(n) over all integers between 2 and n that were not sieved by primes not greater than x.\n\n## Performance and Extensions\n\nThe algorithm can be extended to compute sums of primes and primes in arithmetic progressions. Additionally, both Lucy DP and the black algorithm can be optimized using Fenwick trees, reducing the complexity to O(N^{2/3}).\n\nThe basic Lucy_Hedgehog algorithm without optimization uses approximately O(n^{3/4}) time and O(√n) space, making it more efficient than the classical Sieve of Eratosthenes for large values.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9da4c680-a7b0-439a-ab5c-4f174667a2cc","timestamp":"2026-04-04T15:12:26.042Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9ab58436-feac-4e13-854b-d18096955aae","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"33140f23-a580-4bd9-95f3-32a2246a99e4","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"majestic-juggling-whale"}
    {"parentUuid":"942c0a8c-0726-4e17-9758-06d9485796ff","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b51d0d0e-11a7-49cc-a304-5ddf3d02ce8f","agentId":"a9a175726ae9963f1","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CJtNpYRwCNhk1ygqiynp3s","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Hiary computing Riemann zeta critical line faster algorithm 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function\",\"url\":\"https://people.math.osu.edu/hiary.1/fastmethods.html\"},{\"title\":\"[0711.5005] Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/0711.5005\"},{\"title\":\"Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function\",\"url\":\"https://annals.math.princeton.edu/wp-content/uploads/annals-v174-n2-p04-p.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function Ghaith Hiary\",\"url\":\"https://people.math.osu.edu/hiary.1/talk.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/1901255_Fast_methods_to_compute_the_Riemann_zeta_function\"},{\"title\":\"NEW COMPUTATIONS OF THE RIEMANN ZETA FUNCTION ON THE CRITICAL LINE\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1607.00709\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Fast Method for Locating Peak Values of the Riemann Zeta Function on the Critical Line\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277308911_Fast_Method_for_Locating_Peak_Values_of_the_Riemann_Zeta_Function_on_the_Critical_Line\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Fast-methods-to-compute-the-Riemann-zeta-function-Hiary/704ad3cad6c2617cbe3f013b2ffb8c287018ea95\"},{\"title\":\"Fast methods to compute the Riemann zeta function : Ghaith Ayesh Hiary : Free Download, Borrow, and Streaming : Internet Archive\",\"url\":\"https://archive.org/details/arxiv-0711.5005\"},{\"title\":\"Ghaith A. Hiary - OSU Math\",\"url\":\"https://people.math.osu.edu/hiary.1/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding Ghaith Hiary's work on computing the Riemann zeta function on the critical line with faster algorithms:\n\n## Main Achievements\n\nThe fastest available algorithm for evaluating zeta at a single point has an asymptotic running time of about T^(4/13+o(1)), which is approximately 0.307.\n\nThe Riemann zeta function on the critical line can be computed using the Riemann-Siegel formula, Schönhage's method, or Heath-Brown's method, with complexities having exponents 1/2, 3/8 (=0.375), and 1/3 respectively.\n\n## Hiary's Fast Methods\n\nThree new fast methods to compute zeta are presented - one very simple method with complexity exponent 2/5, a second method with complexity exponent 1/3, and a third method with complexity exponent 4/13 (approximately 0.307).\n\nThe fastest method has complexity t^(4/13+o(1)), which improves by a noticeable margin on the \"complexity bound\" of t^(1/3+o(1)).\n\n## Implementation and Applications\n\nOne algorithm permits the numerical evaluation of ζ(σ + iT) in T^(1/3+o(1)) time. The main new ingredient in computations of the Riemann zeta function around large values and high zeros is an implementation of Hiary's fast algorithm for numerically evaluating quadratic exponential sums.\n\nThe search results provided information from earlier work (primarily 2007-2011 publications), but did not contain specific information about 2024-2025 developments in this area.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"4f778ce0-ee26-4fdf-ad94-ea1b9c54abe1","timestamp":"2026-04-04T15:12:26.289Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"942c0a8c-0726-4e17-9758-06d9485796ff","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"33140f23-a580-4bd9-95f3-32a2246a99e4","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"majestic-juggling-whale"}
