    {"parentUuid":"efff64f4-2d9a-4339-99e7-3d69eadf2790","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b51d0d0e-11a7-49cc-a304-5ddf3d02ce8f","agentId":"a9a175726ae9963f1","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019BWwNWGfZbBgCvNtys636t","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"hyperbola method divisor sum O(x^{1/3}) why not work Mobius function Mertens\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Summing Multiplicative Functions (Pt. 1) | griff’s math blog!\",\"url\":\"https://gbroxey.github.io/blog/2023/04/30/mult-sum-1.html\"},{\"title\":\"Dirichlet convolution. Part 1: Fast prefix sum computations - Codeforces\",\"url\":\"https://codeforces.com/blog/entry/117635\"},{\"title\":\"Divisor summatory function - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor_summatory_function\"},{\"title\":\"Partial sums of arithmetical functions\",\"url\":\"https://trizenx.blogspot.com/2018/11/partial-sums-of-arithmetical-functions.html\"},{\"title\":\"Dirichlet hyperbola method - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirichlet_hyperbola_method\"},{\"title\":\"A remark on partial sums involving the Möbius function | What's new\",\"url\":\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2009/08/30/an-elementary-inequality-involving-the-mobius-function/\"},{\"title\":\"Dirichlet hyperbola method | What's new - Terry Tao\",\"url\":\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/tag/dirichlet-hyperbola-method/\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) On Exponential Sums Involving the Divisor Function Over Z\",\"url\":\"https://www.academia.edu/84712399/On_Exponential_Sums_Involving_the_Divisor_Function_Over_Z\"},{\"title\":\"Möbius function - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_function\"},{\"title\":\"DIRICHLET CHARACTERS AND THE METHOD OF HYPERBOLAS E. CHERNYSH Contents 1.\",\"url\":\"https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~echern2/repo/dirichlet.pdf\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found relevant information about this topic. The key insight comes from Terry Tao's discussion of why the hyperbola method doesn't work as effectively for the Möbius function and Mertens function compared to other divisor sums.\n\nThe inefficiency when using the hyperbola method for the Möbius function compared to the divisor function can be attributed to the signed nature of the Möbius function, which causes some cancellation in the divisor sum expansion that needs to be compensated for with improved estimates.\n\nMore specifically, if one wishes to use the standard divisor sum representation with the Möbius function to compute sums, from Dirichlet series methods one ends up with estimates that are useless as lower bounds and recovers only the classical Chebyshev estimate as an upper bound.\n\nThe fundamental issue is structural: the divisor function approach works well because it's non-negative, allowing the hyperbola method's geometric lattice-point counting intuition to provide tight bounds. However, the signed nature of the Möbius function causes cancellation in the divisor sum expansion, which prevents straightforward application of the hyperbola method from achieving better than O(x^(1/3)) complexity bounds. This is why different computational techniques, such as sieving methods combined with recursive formulas, are needed to efficiently compute the Mertens function and related sums.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"601e3e17-1c27-44c7-859d-839bb1a0a01c","timestamp":"2026-04-04T15:12:46.822Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"efff64f4-2d9a-4339-99e7-3d69eadf2790","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"33140f23-a580-4bd9-95f3-32a2246a99e4","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"majestic-juggling-whale"}
    {"parentUuid":"9841fa8c-a4ef-4975-9ea0-d911f2ad8a99","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b51d0d0e-11a7-49cc-a304-5ddf3d02ce8f","agentId":"a9a175726ae9963f1","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01975aq6q6epV5V1uQwdQ6ow","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Helfgott Thompson O(x^{3/5}) Mertens function does it apply to pi(x) prime counting\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Prime-counting function - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime-counting_function\"},{\"title\":\"Prime Counting Function -- from Wolfram MathWorld\",\"url\":\"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeCountingFunction.html\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] An improved sieve of Eratosthenes | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/An-improved-sieve-of-Eratosthenes-Helfgott/97a54acb70f05619ac9a05a91da62e34874b6df5\"},{\"title\":\"H. A. Helfgott, L. Thompson Res. Number Theory (2023) 9:6\",\"url\":\"https://pure.mpg.de/pubman/item/item_3486843_2/component/file_3486847/Helfgott-Thompson_Summing+mu(n)_a+faster+elementary+algorith_2023.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"A prime counting function I have never seen | Free Math Help Forum\",\"url\":\"https://www.freemathhelp.com/forum/threads/a-prime-counting-function-i-have-never-seen.139278/\"},{\"title\":\"Prime number theorem - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem\"},{\"title\":\"New bounds for the prime counting function \\\\pi(x) - ADS\",\"url\":\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014arXiv1409.1780A/abstract\"},{\"title\":\"pi(x) (prime counting function) | Desmos\",\"url\":\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/obtpk43prp\"},{\"title\":\"An Approximation of the Prime Counting Function and a New Representation of the Riemann Zeta Function\",\"url\":\"https://www.mdpi.com/2227-7390/12/17/2624\"},{\"title\":\"Prime Counting Function Calculator - Online Primes Less Than Counter\",\"url\":\"https://www.dcode.fr/prime-number-pi-count\"}]\n\nThe search results contain information about bounds on the prime counting function π(x), but don't directly address whether the O(x^{3/5}) bound applies to the Mertens function. Let me search more specifically for Helfgott-Thompson results on the Mertens function.\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Mertens function - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mertens_function\"},{\"title\":\"[2101.08773] Summing $μ(n)$: a faster elementary algorithm\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.08773\"},{\"title\":\"Computations of the Mertens Function and Improved Bounds on the Mertens Conjecture\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309484116_Computations_of_the_Mertens_Function_and_Improved_Bounds_on_the_Mertens_Conjecture\"},{\"title\":\"H. A. Helfgott, L. Thompson Res. Number Theory (2023) 9:6\",\"url\":\"https://pure.mpg.de/pubman/item/item_3486843_2/component/file_3486847/Helfgott-Thompson_Summing+mu(n)_a+faster+elementary+algorith_2023.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"SUMMING µ(n): A FASTER ELEMENTARY ALGORITHM\",\"url\":\"https://people.maths.bris.ac.uk/~jb12407/ANTS-XV/papers/ANTS-XV_helfgott-thompson.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Summing $$\\\\mu (n)$$ : a faster elementary algorithm | Research in Number Theory | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40993-022-00408-8\"},{\"title\":\"Mertens function — Grokipedia\",\"url\":\"https://grokipedia.com/page/Mertens_function\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Summing $$\\\\mu (n)$$: a faster elementary algorithm\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/366126419_Summing_mu_n_a_faster_elementary_algorithm\"},{\"title\":\"Computation of the Totient Summatory Function\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.07386\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] Summing μ ( n ) : a faster elementary algorithm. | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Summing-%CE%BC-(-n-)-:-a-faster-elementary-algorithm.-Helfgott-Thompson/53e96664644bdb6481f429761791df75ddf00df1\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I can now provide you with a comprehensive answer:\n\n## Helfgott-Thompson Algorithm and the O(x^{3/5}) Bound\n\nA further improvement by Harald Helfgott and Lola Thompson in 2021 improves this to O(x^{3/5}(log x)^{3/5+ε}) for computing the **Mertens function**, which is defined as M(x) = Σ_{n≤x} μ(n), where μ(n) is the Möbius function.\n\n## Does It Apply to π(x)?\n\n**No**, the O(x^{3/5}) bound does **not** directly apply to the prime counting function π(x). The Helfgott-Thompson result is specifically an algorithm for **computing the Mertens function M(x)**, not for computing π(x).\n\nHowever, there is an indirect relationship: ψ(x)=M(x/2)log 2+M(x/3)log 3+M(x/4)log 4+⋯, where ψ(x) is the Chebyshev function, which is related to π(x). So while the O(x^{3/5}) bound for computing M(x) could potentially be utilized as part of a larger algorithm to estimate π(x) through the Chebyshev function, it is not a direct bound on π(x) itself.\n\nThis is the first improvement in the exponent of x for an elementary algorithm since 1985, making it a significant advancement in computational number theory.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b3cdfec2-44eb-4f09-9209-954d5d3be4dc","timestamp":"2026-04-04T15:12:48.640Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9841fa8c-a4ef-4975-9ea0-d911f2ad8a99","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"33140f23-a580-4bd9-95f3-32a2246a99e4","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"majestic-juggling-whale"}
