## Session 11 — Updated Final Status

The matrix powering research agent delivered a **comprehensive survey** that corrects an important nuance:

### The Precise Picture at the TC^0/NC^1 Boundary

| Problem | In TC^0? | Source |
|---------|----------|--------|
| Scalar x^n mod m | **YES** | HAB 2002 |
| Product of N given integers | **YES** | HAB 2002 |
| Product of N given k×k matrices (k≥3) | **NO** (unless TC^0=NC^1) | Mereghetti-Palano 2000 |
| M^n for **fixed** k×k matrix | **YES** | Mereghetti-Palano 2000 |
| M^n for **growing** d×d matrix (d=polylog(n)) | **OPEN** | — |
| α^k in F_{2^n} | **YES** | Healy-Viola 2006 |

Our AKS reduction requires the **growing-dimension case** — the only genuinely open row. The bottleneck: combining polylog(n) eigenvalue powers requires depth O(log log n), which is not constant.

This places the problem precisely at the **TC^0/NC^1 boundary** — one of the most important open questions in circuit complexity. Resolving it in either direction would be a major breakthrough.

